		</div>
		<h1 class='ui header'>U.S. has changed in key ways in the past decade, from tech use to demographics</h1><div class="bylines">By <a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/staff/katherine-schaeffer"><span class="author">Katherine Schaeffer</span></a></div><div id="js-toc-mobile" accordion-tab-only="false"></div>	</header>
	<div class="post-content">
		<p>The past decade in the United States has seen technological advancements, demographic shifts and major changes in public opinion. Pew Research Center has tracked these developments through surveys, demographic analyses and other research. As the 2010s draw to a close, here are key ways the country looks different from 10 years ago:</p>
<p><strong>From smartphones to social media, tech use has <a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2018/09/28/internet-social-media-use-and-device-ownership-in-u-s-have-plateaued-after-years-of-growth/">become the norm</a>. </strong>As of 2019, nine-in-ten U.S. adults say they go online, 81% say they own a smartphone and 72% say they use social media. Growth in adoption of some technologies has slowed in recent years, in some instances because there just aren’t many non-users left, especially <a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2019/09/09/us-generations-technology-use/">among younger generations</a>. For example, 93% of Millennials (ages 23 to 38 in 2019) own smartphones, and nearly 100% say they use the internet.</p>
<p><img class="aligncenter wp-image-325207 size-640-wide" src="https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_tech.png?w=640" alt="Use of mobile devices, social media in U.S. rose sharply in 2010s" width="640" height="510" srcset="https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_tech.png 1280w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_tech.png?resize=300,239 300w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_tech.png?resize=768,612 768w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_tech.png?resize=1024,816 1024w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_tech.png?resize=160,128 160w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_tech.png?resize=508,405 508w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_tech.png?resize=200,159 200w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_tech.png?resize=260,207 260w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_tech.png?resize=310,247 310w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_tech.png?resize=420,335 420w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_tech.png?resize=640,510 640w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_tech.png?resize=740,590 740w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" /><span id="more-325200"></span></p>
<p><strong>Social media is now a key pathway to news for Americans. </strong>In 2018, <a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2018/12/10/social-media-outpaces-print-newspapers-in-t">for the first time</a>, social media sites surpassed print newspapers as a news source for Americans. One-in-five adults said they often get news from social media, slightly higher than the share who often did so from print newspapers (16%). Among social media sites, <a href="https://www.journalism.org/2019/10/02/americans-are-wary-of-the-role-social-media-sites-play-in-delivering-the-news/">Facebook dominates</a> in terms of news consumption: Around half of all U.S. adults (52%) now say they get news there.</p>
<img class="aligncenter wp-image-325209 size-420-wide" src="https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_social-media.png?w=420" alt="Social media sites as pathways to news" width="420" height="646" srcset="https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_social-media.png 840w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_social-media.png?resize=195,300 195w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_social-media.png?resize=768,1181 768w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_social-media.png?resize=666,1024 666w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_social-media.png?resize=160,246 160w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_social-media.png?resize=263,405 263w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_social-media.png?resize=200,308 200w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_social-media.png?resize=260,400 260w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_social-media.png?resize=310,477 310w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_social-media.png?resize=420,646 420w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_social-media.png?resize=640,984 640w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_social-media.png?resize=740,1138 740w" sizes="(max-width: 420px) 100vw, 420px" />
<p><strong>Millennials have surpassed Generation Xers as <a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2018/04/11/millennials-largest-generation-us-labor-force/">the largest generation</a> in the U.S. labor force.</strong> There were 57 million Millennials (born 1981 to 1996) working or looking for work in 2018. That was more than the 53 million Gen Xers (born 1965 to 1980) and well ahead of the 38 million Baby Boomers (born 1946 to 1964).</p>
<img class="aligncenter wp-image-325232 size-640-wide" src="https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.05.17_genWorkforceRevised.png?w=640" alt="Millennials became the largest generation in the labor force in 2016" width="640" height="386" srcset="https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.05.17_genWorkforceRevised.png 1280w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.05.17_genWorkforceRevised.png?resize=300,181 300w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.05.17_genWorkforceRevised.png?resize=768,463 768w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.05.17_genWorkforceRevised.png?resize=1024,618 1024w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.05.17_genWorkforceRevised.png?resize=160,97 160w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.05.17_genWorkforceRevised.png?resize=672,405 672w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.05.17_genWorkforceRevised.png?resize=200,121 200w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.05.17_genWorkforceRevised.png?resize=260,157 260w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.05.17_genWorkforceRevised.png?resize=310,187 310w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.05.17_genWorkforceRevised.png?resize=420,253 420w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.05.17_genWorkforceRevised.png?resize=640,386 640w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.05.17_genWorkforceRevised.png?resize=740,446 740w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" />
<p><strong>Following the Great Recession, the U.S. unemployment rate declined from a near record high level (9.5%) in the second quarter of 2010 to a <a href="https://www.pewsocialtrends.org/essay/two-recessions-two-recoveries/">near-record low</a> (3.5%) in the second quarter of 2019 </strong>(figures are non-seasonally adjusted). Despite the downward trend in unemployment, the recovery in other labor market indicators has been anemic to absent in the post-Great Recession era. For example, the U.S. <em>employment</em> rate in 2019 is several percentage points lower than it was at the start of the Great Recession in 2007, primarily because of the aging U.S. population.</p>
<img class="aligncenter size-420-wide wp-image-325205" src="https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_unemployment.png?w=420" alt="Following Great Recession, U.S. unemployment rate has fallen to near-record low" width="420" height="419" srcset="https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_unemployment.png 840w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_unemployment.png?resize=150,150 150w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_unemployment.png?resize=300,300 300w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_unemployment.png?resize=768,766 768w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_unemployment.png?resize=160,160 160w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_unemployment.png?resize=100,100 100w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_unemployment.png?resize=406,405 406w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_unemployment.png?resize=75,75 75w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_unemployment.png?resize=140,140 140w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_unemployment.png?resize=200,200 200w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_unemployment.png?resize=260,259 260w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_unemployment.png?resize=310,309 310w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_unemployment.png?resize=420,419 420w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_unemployment.png?resize=640,638 640w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_unemployment.png?resize=740,738 740w" sizes="(max-width: 420px) 100vw, 420px" />
<p><strong>The 2010s will likely be the <a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2019/10/01/the-number-of-people-in-the-average-u-s-household-is-going-up-for-the-first-time-in-over-160-years/">first decade in at least 160 years</a> to see an increase in the average number of people living in U.S. households.</strong> This is in part because of the rising number of Americans living in multigenerational households. In 2016, a record 64 million people, or 20% of the U.S. population, lived with <a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2018/04/05/a-record-64-million-americans-live-in-multigenerational-households/">multiple generations under one roof</a>, even with improvements in the U.S. economy since the Great Recession. Another factor behind the increase in household size: More Americans are “doubled up” in <a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2018/01/31/more-adults-now-share-their-living-space-driven-in-part-by-parents-living-with-their-adult-children/">shared living quarters</a>.</p>
<img class="size-310-wide wp-image-320913 aligncenter" src="https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/FT_19.09.24_HouseholdSize_1.png?w=310" alt="This decade will likely be the first in at least 160 years in which American households have more people" width="310" height="530" srcset="https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/FT_19.09.24_HouseholdSize_1.png 620w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/FT_19.09.24_HouseholdSize_1.png?resize=175,300 175w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/FT_19.09.24_HouseholdSize_1.png?resize=599,1024 599w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/FT_19.09.24_HouseholdSize_1.png?resize=160,274 160w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/FT_19.09.24_HouseholdSize_1.png?resize=237,405 237w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/FT_19.09.24_HouseholdSize_1.png?resize=200,342 200w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/FT_19.09.24_HouseholdSize_1.png?resize=260,445 260w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/FT_19.09.24_HouseholdSize_1.png?resize=310,530 310w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/FT_19.09.24_HouseholdSize_1.png?resize=420,718 420w" sizes="(max-width: 310px) 100vw, 310px" />
<p><strong>Nonwhites now account for the majority of the nation’s newborns, as well as the majority of K-12 students in public schools. </strong>More than half of newborn babies in the U.S. are <a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2016/06/23/its-official-minority-babies-are-the-majority-among-the-nations-infants-but-only-just/">racial or ethnic minorities</a>, a threshold first crossed in 2013. Nonwhite students also account for the majority of the nation’s K-12 public school students. As of fall 2018, children from racial and ethnic minority groups were projected to make up <a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2019/07/31/kindergarten-demographics-in-us/">52.9% of public K-12 students</a>.</p>
<img class="aligncenter size-310-wide wp-image-318113" src="https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/FT_19.08.30_KindergartenDemographics_Hispanics-growing-share-K-12-public-school-students.png?w=310" alt="Hispanics are growing as a share of K-12 public school students" width="310" height="534" srcset="https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/FT_19.08.30_KindergartenDemographics_Hispanics-growing-share-K-12-public-school-students.png 620w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/FT_19.08.30_KindergartenDemographics_Hispanics-growing-share-K-12-public-school-students.png?resize=174,300 174w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/FT_19.08.30_KindergartenDemographics_Hispanics-growing-share-K-12-public-school-students.png?resize=595,1024 595w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/FT_19.08.30_KindergartenDemographics_Hispanics-growing-share-K-12-public-school-students.png?resize=160,275 160w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/FT_19.08.30_KindergartenDemographics_Hispanics-growing-share-K-12-public-school-students.png?resize=235,405 235w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/FT_19.08.30_KindergartenDemographics_Hispanics-growing-share-K-12-public-school-students.png?resize=200,344 200w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/FT_19.08.30_KindergartenDemographics_Hispanics-growing-share-K-12-public-school-students.png?resize=260,447 260w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/FT_19.08.30_KindergartenDemographics_Hispanics-growing-share-K-12-public-school-students.png?resize=310,534 310w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/07/FT_19.08.30_KindergartenDemographics_Hispanics-growing-share-K-12-public-school-students.png?resize=420,723 420w" sizes="(max-width: 310px) 100vw, 310px" />
<p><strong>It’s become more common for Americans to attend church a few times a year or less (54%) than monthly or more (45%).</strong> This is <a href="https://www.pewforum.org/2019/10/17/in-u-s-decline-of-christianity-continues-at-rapid-pace/">just one measure</a> by which the religious landscape of the country has changed. Since 2009, the share of Americans who describe their religious identity as atheist, agnostic or “nothing in particular” has grown from 17% to 26%, while the share who describe themselves as Christians has declined from 77% to 65%.</p>
<img class="aligncenter size-310-wide wp-image-325215" src="https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_church2.png?w=310" alt="In U.S., church attendance is declining" width="310" height="646" srcset="https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_church2.png 620w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_church2.png?resize=144,300 144w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_church2.png?resize=491,1024 491w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_church2.png?resize=154,320 154w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_church2.png?resize=194,405 194w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_church2.png?resize=200,417 200w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_church2.png?resize=260,542 260w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_church2.png?resize=310,646 310w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_church2.png?resize=420,875 420w" sizes="(max-width: 310px) 100vw, 310px" />
<p><strong>Americans increasingly support the legalization of marijuana.</strong> Two-thirds of U.S. adults <a href="https://www.pewresearch.org/fact-tank/2019/11/14/americans-support-marijuana-legalization/">now back legalization</a>. A little less than a decade ago, in 2010, fewer than half (41%) did so. The change in public sentiment has been accompanied by a changing legal landscape: As of this year, 11 states and the District of Columbia have legalized small amounts of marijuana for adult recreational use, while many others have legalized it for medical use. The drug remains illegal under federal law.</p>
<img class="aligncenter size-310-wide wp-image-323965" src="https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/FT_19.12.12_MarijuanaUpdate.png?w=310" alt="U.S. public opinion on legalizing marijuana, 1969-2019" width="310" height="509" srcset="https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/FT_19.12.12_MarijuanaUpdate.png 942w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/FT_19.12.12_MarijuanaUpdate.png?resize=183,300 183w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/FT_19.12.12_MarijuanaUpdate.png?resize=768,1261 768w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/FT_19.12.12_MarijuanaUpdate.png?resize=624,1024 624w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/FT_19.12.12_MarijuanaUpdate.png?resize=160,263 160w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/FT_19.12.12_MarijuanaUpdate.png?resize=935,1536 935w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/FT_19.12.12_MarijuanaUpdate.png?resize=247,405 247w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/FT_19.12.12_MarijuanaUpdate.png?resize=200,328 200w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/FT_19.12.12_MarijuanaUpdate.png?resize=260,427 260w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/FT_19.12.12_MarijuanaUpdate.png?resize=310,509 310w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/FT_19.12.12_MarijuanaUpdate.png?resize=420,690 420w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/FT_19.12.12_MarijuanaUpdate.png?resize=640,1051 640w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/11/FT_19.12.12_MarijuanaUpdate.png?resize=740,1215 740w" sizes="(max-width: 310px) 100vw, 310px" />
<p><strong>Same-sex marriage has the backing of a majority of U.S. adults.</strong> Same-sex marriage is another policy area where <a href="https://www.people-press.org/2019/05/14/majority-of-public-favors-same-sex-marriage-but-divisions-persist/">support surpassed opposition</a> during the 2010s. As of this year, 61% of Americans favor allowing gays and lesbians to marry legally. In 2015, the U.S. Supreme Court issued its landmark <a href="https://www.scotusblog.com/case-files/cases/obergefell-v-hodges/">Obergefell v. Hodges ruling</a>, which established that same-sex couples have a constitutional right to marry.</p>
<img class="aligncenter size-310-wide wp-image-325225" src="https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_same-sex-marriage.png?w=310" alt="Public remains supportive of same-sex marriage; wide partisan gap persists" width="310" height="740" srcset="https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_same-sex-marriage.png 620w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_same-sex-marriage.png?resize=126,300 126w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_same-sex-marriage.png?resize=429,1024 429w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_same-sex-marriage.png?resize=134,320 134w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_same-sex-marriage.png?resize=170,405 170w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_same-sex-marriage.png?resize=200,477 200w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_same-sex-marriage.png?resize=260,621 260w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_same-sex-marriage.png?resize=310,740 310w, https://www.pewresearch.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/FT_19.12.17_DecadeChanges_same-sex-marriage.png?resize=420,1003 420w" sizes="(max-width: 310px) 100vw, 310px" />
<p><em>Note: This post contains updated data on the use of smartphones and other technologies, as well as the generational makeup of the U.S. labor force. </em></p>
